Part I - Prosper Loan Data Analysis And Exploration¶

by Maryam OYEYIOLA¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

This data dictionary explains the variables in the data set.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 77557 loans listed in this dataset, with 23 features. including LoanStatus BorrowerRate IncomeRange, StatedMonthlyIncome LoanOriginalAmount LoanOriginationDate Recommendations ListingCategory, among others. Most of the features are categorical in nature

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am mostl interested in finding out which features contribute to the amount of loan a borrower gets. I can already assume some features like IsBorrowerHomeowner and IncomeRange contribute to how much loan is disburesed, but I am not sure of the extent. While features like Recommendations and LoanOriginationQuarter may probably have no effect of the amount disbursed, I am interested in finding that out as well.

A good amount of recommendations can go a long way in solidifying the decision of either giving an individual a loan or not

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that StatedMonthlyIncome and IncomeRange will have a huge effect on the amount of loan a borrower will get. Borrowers with a high income may be elligible for higher amount of loan, while those whose income is on the lower side may be elligible for lower amount

The DebtToIncomeRatio of a borrower can also contribute to whether they get a loan or not and how much they get. The lower the percentage/ratio the better the chances of getting a loan as well as a substantial amount

IsBorrowerHomeowner has the tendency of contributing to the loan amount. The value of the property matters as well, but just having a listed property can go a long way in securing a loan amount, be it within the range of the property's value.

Most of the loan are still current and active. About 90% of borrowers who have taken out loans are employed and earn at least 1-dolloar per year

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I increased the bin size of LoanOriginalAmount, BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR to be able to take a closer look at the distribution. I detected outliers in LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment and DebtToIncomeRatio. I let the outliers in LoanOriginalAmount because they do not seem to make substantial change and it contributes to the statistical averaging of loan amounts per year. The outliers are just increasing amounts of loans.

The outliers in MonthlyLoanPayment and DebtToIncomeRatio were removed. The distribution of MonthlyLoanPayment was right skewed before tidying. After tidying the distribution became more evenly spread and there was also a spike, resulting in a unimodal distribution. DebtToIncomeRatio maintain the same shape of distribution, before and after removing the outliers

Paying back the loan and borrowerrate and BorroweAPR on time, that is over a short period of 12 to 36 months increases the prosper score
